geneVariantDescriptions.description: TMB high indicates a high tumor mutational burden.

references.title: External Reference Not Available (N/A)

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase Ib trial, patients with a neuroendocrine tumor with high tumor mutational burden (TMB high, greater than 9.9 muts/Mb, n=4) compared to patients with a TMB less than 9.9 muts/Mb (n=34) demonstrated a greater objective response rate (75% vs 16.1%) and disease control rate (100% vs 29%) when treated with Toripalimab (JS001) (PMID: 32086343; NCT03167853).

references.title: Efficacy, safety and biomarkers of toripalimab in patients with recurrent or metastatic neuroendocrine neoplasms: a multiple-center phase Ib trial.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a retrospective analysis, patients with esophagogastric cancer (n=126) and a high tumor mutational burden (TMB) (>8.8 mutations/Mb) demonstrated an improved overall survival and progression-free survival compared to those patients with a low TMB when treated with an unspecified PD-1 antibody (PMID: 30643254).

references.title: Tumor mutational load predicts survival after immunotherapy across multiple cancer types.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a retrospective analysis, patients with estrogen-receptor positive breast cancer (n=24) and a high tumor mutational burden (TMB) (>6.8 mutations/Mb) demonstrated an improved overall survival compared to those patients with a low TMB when treated with an unspecified PD-1 antibody (PMID: 30643254).

references.title: Tumor mutational load predicts survival after immunotherapy across multiple cancer types.

references.title: Tumor mutational load predicts survival after immunotherapy across multiple cancer types.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase I/II trial, Toripalimab (JS001) treatment resulted in an objective response rate (ORR) of 12.1% (7/58, 7 partial responses) and a disease control rate of 39.7% (23/58) in patients with advanced gastric cancer, the TMB-high group demonstrated improved ORR (4/12, 33.3% vs 3/42, 7.1%, p=0.017) and overall survival (14.6 vs 4.0 months, HR=0.48, p=0.038) compared to the TMB-low group (PMID: 31236579; NCT02915432).

references.title: Safety, efficacy and tumor mutational burden as a biomarker of overall survival benefit in chemo-refractory gastric cancer treated with toripalimab, a PD-1 antibody in phase Ib/II clinical trial NCT02915432.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a retrospective analysis, patients with melanoma (n=321) and a high tumor mutational burden (TMB) (>30.7 mutations/Mb) demonstrated an improved overall survival and progression-free survival compared to those patients with a low TMB when treated with a combination of an unspecified CTLA-4 antibody and an unspecified PD-L1 antibody (PMID: 30643254).

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase Ib/II trial, Keytruda (pembrolizumab) treatment of non-small cell lung cancer patients with high mutational burden (greater than 200 mutations) had a 59% overall response rate (10/17) as compared to 12% (2/17) of patients with low mutational burden (PMID: 25765070).

references.title: Cancer immunology. Mutational landscape determines sensitivity to PD-1 blockade in non-small cell lung cancer.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a clinical study, immunotherapies including Tecentriq (atezolizumab) (n=5), Opdivo (nivolumab) (n=17), Keytruda (pembrolizumab) (n=36), and Camrelizumab (SHR-1210) (n=20) resulted in improved durable clinical benefit rate (46.2% vs 18.4%, p=0.02) and median progression-free survival (116 vs 60 days, p=0.0025) in patients with TMB-high (top 33%, >10Muts/Mb by NGS, n=26) non-small cell lung cancer compared to patients with TMB-low tumors (n=49) (PMID: 31085721).

references.title: Comprehensive Genomic Profiling Identifies Novel Genetic Predictors of Response to Anti-PD-(L)1 Therapies in Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a meta-analysis, treatment with immune checkpoint inhibitors including Tecentriq (atezolizumab), Opdivo (nivolumab), Yervoy (ipilimumab), and Keytruda (pembrolizumab) resulted in improved progression-free survival (HR=0.41, p<0.001) and overall survival (HR=0.26, p=0.009) in non-small cell lung cancer patients with high TMB compared to patients with low TMB (PMID: 31290993).

references.title: Association of Survival and Immune-Related Biomarkers With Immunotherapy in Patients With Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer: A Meta-analysis and Individual Patient-Level Analysis.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase III trial (CheckMate 026), patients with stage IV or recurrent non-small cell lung cancer with high tumor mutational burden (TMB) demonstrated a response rate of 48% (n=47) following treatment with Opdivo (nivolumab) compared to a response rate of 28% (n=60) in patients treated with chemotherapy, and a median progression-free survival of 9.7 months vs. 5.8 months with chemotherapy treatment (PMID: 28636851; NCT02041533).

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase I/II trial (CheckMate 032), Opdivo (nivolumab) and Yervoy (ipilimumab) combination therapy resulted in higher objective response rate in small cell lung cancer patients with high (46.2%, 12/26) tumor mutational burden (TMB) compared to patients with low (22.2%, 6/27) or medium (16.0%, 4/25) TMB, higher estimated 1-year progression-free survival rate (30.0%, 6.2%, 8.0%), and higher estimated 1-year overall survival rate (62.4%, 23.4%, 19.6%) (PMID: 29731394; NCT01928394).

references.title: Tumor Mutational Burden and Efficacy of Nivolumab Monotherapy and in Combination with Ipilimumab in Small-Cell Lung Cancer.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a retrospective analysis, immune-checkpoint inhibitors (Keytruda (pembrolizumab), n=7; Opdivo (nivolumab), n=24; Opdivo (nivolumab) plus Yervoy (ipilimumab), n=21) resulted in significantly improved median progression-free survival (3.3 vs 1.2 mo, HR=0.37, p<0.01) and median overall survival (10.4 vs 2.5 mo, HR=0.38, p<0.01) in small cell lung cancer patients with high tumor mutational burden (TMB>9.68mut/MB) compared to patients with low TMB (TMB less or equal to 9.68mut/MB) (PMID: 30922388).

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase III (CheckMate 227) trial, Opdivo (nivolumab) and Yervoy (ipilimumab) combination treatment resulted in prolonged progression-free survival (7.2 vs 5.5 months, HR=0.58, p<0.001) and higher objective response rate (45.3% vs 26.9%) compared to chemotherapy in non-small cell lung cancer patients with a high tumor mutational burden (PMID: 29658845; NCT02477826).

references.title: Nivolumab plus Ipilimumab in Lung Cancer with a High Tumor Mutational Burden.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase I trial, Yervoy (ipilimumab) treatment resulted in an overall survival advantage in melanoma patients that were ipilimumab-naive with high tumor mutational burden (greater than 100 mutations) (PMID: 29033130; NCT01621490).

references.title: Tumor and Microenvironment Evolution during Immunotherapy with Nivolumab.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a clinical study, Yervoy (ipilimumab) treatment resulted in a 68% (17/25) overall survival advantage of melanoma patients with high tumor mutational burden (greater than 100 mutations), but high TMB was not independently predictive of response (PMID: 25409260).

references.title: Genetic basis for clinical response to CTLA-4 blockade in melanoma.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a Phase II trial (TAPUR), Keytruda (pembrolizumab) treatment resulted in a disease control rate of 37% (10/28, 6 complete response or partial response, 4 stable disease at 16 weeks) in patients with metastatic breast cancer with high mutational burden (9-37 Muts/Mb), with a median progression-free survival of 10.6 weeks and a median overall survival of 31.6 months (J Clin Oncol 37, 2019 (suppl; abstr 1014); NCT02693535).

references.title: Pembrolizumab (P) in patients (pts) with metastatic breast cancer (MBC) with high tumor mutational burden (HTMB): Results from the Targeted Agent and Profiling Utilization Registry (TAPUR) Study.
